---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Newsletter from '../components/Newsletter.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Living — Living Sovereignty"
  description="The Living pillar at AfterChildren. Aging in place, downsizing, 55+ communities, CCRC, geographic relocation, international retirement. Where and how you live for the next 30 years — decided deliberately, not by default."
>
  <!-- PILLAR HERO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="pillar-hero">
      <p class="pillar-hero__eyebrow">Sovereignty 05</p>
      <h1 class="pillar-hero__title">
        Living.<br />
        <em>The roof over the next thirty years.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="pillar-hero__lede">
        The single decision with the highest variance and the least examination in the second half of life. Where you live, and in what kind of structure, decides everything else: how isolated you become, how expensive your care will be, how often you see your grandchildren, how safe you are when you fall at 78, and what the move-out from your final home will cost. Most parents make this decision by default — by staying in the house they raised the kids in, which becomes a barrier years before they notice — or by panic, when a hospitalization at 82 forces a 60-day move into the first assisted-living facility with an open bed. The deliberate version of this decision is dramatically better. The window to make it is roughly age 60 to 72.
      </p>
      <div class="pillar-hero__meta">
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">20</span> planned articles in this pillar</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">0</span> live now</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span>First article ships next week</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHERE TO START -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="start-panel">
      <p class="start-panel__eyebrow">Where to start</p>
      <h2 class="start-panel__title">Three moves. This year. Before the decision gets made for you.</h2>
      <ol class="start-panel__list">
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Audit your current home</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Walk through it as if you were 80. The stairs. The shower. The thresholds. The lighting at 2 a.m. The width of the doorways. The reach to the top shelves. Most homes built before 2010 are catastrophically unsafe for an aging body. The modifications that make a difference cost $5,000 to $40,000. The cost of not making them is the broken hip, the nursing home admission, the panic move. Run the audit at 62. Plan the modifications by 65. Complete them by 70.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Visit three structures you might live in</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">A 55+ community. A CCRC. An assisted-living facility. Not because you are moving, but because you have to know what these places are like before you might need one. The information asymmetry between the people who already live in these structures and the people who haven't yet seen one is enormous. Most parents make this decision after one panicked tour. Three deliberate visits, ten years out, produce a dramatically different choice.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Run the geography math</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Cost of living, state income tax, property tax, proximity to children, proximity to medical care, climate, social network. Most parents make the geographic decision by inertia and lose six figures over 25 years to it. The relocation calculation does not require a financial advisor — it requires one afternoon with a spreadsheet. The question is not just where you want to live. It is where the math says you should live, and how close to that answer you are willing to get.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURED MANIFESTO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="featured">
      <p class="featured__eyebrow">Start here</p>
      <a href="/manifestos/moving-in-with-kids-fails" class="featured__card">
        <div class="featured__meta">
          <span class="featured__tag">Manifesto</span>
          <span class="featured__time">14 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="featured__title">Why Moving In With Your Kids Almost Always Fails</h2>
        <p class="featured__excerpt">The 70% failure rate nobody warned you about, the three situations where it actually works, and the alternative most parents do not consider — relocate to your adult child's region, but to your own home or apartment, not into their household. The single highest-leverage decision in this entire pillar.</p>
        <span class="featured__cta">Read the essay <span class="featured__arrow">→</span></span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE SIX LIVING SUB-PILLARS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="subpillars">
      <p class="subpillars__eyebrow">The six living domains</p>
      <h2 class="subpillars__title">The living sovereignty work, broken down.</h2>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">01</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Aging in place</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The default plan, and for many parents, the right plan — but only if the house is engineered for it. The two-story Colonial that worked at 45 is a falls hazard at 72. The clawfoot tub is a hospital admission waiting to happen. The home that has not been modified for aging is not a home you can age in. The modifications are not expensive relative to the alternative, but they have to be planned at 62 and completed by 70, not improvised after the first fall. The phrase "aging in place" is sold by the home-modification industry as if it were a passive activity. It is not. It is an architectural project, with a budget and a timeline.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Aging in Place: The Modifications That Matter (And the Ones That Are a Waste)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Walk-Through Audit: How to Evaluate Your Home for the Next 30 Years</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Stairlifts, Elevators, and First-Floor Conversions: The Real Math</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Universal Design: What It Is and Why It Costs Less Than Retrofitting</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> When Aging in Place Stops Making Sense (And the Signs You Will Miss)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">02</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Downsizing</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The downsize is the most emotionally loaded financial decision of the second half. Sold too early, you lose the place that anchors your community. Sold too late, you face a forced move at 82 from a position of weakness, with no time to find the right next place. Add the logistics — thirty years of accumulated possessions, of which the adult children want about 4%, the estate sale market wants about 15%, and the rest you will donate or pay to dispose of — and the downsize becomes a multi-year project. Most parents start it too late. The right starting age is 60 to 65. The right completion age is 70 to 72. The wrong age is 80.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Downsizing the Family Home: The Right Age, The Wrong Age</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Thirty Years of Possessions: The Math on What Anyone Actually Wants</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Senior Move Managers: The Service Almost Nobody Knows Exists</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Capital Gains and the Home Sale Exclusion: What the IRS Lets You Keep</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Emotional Cost of the Downsize (And Why It's Worth Paying Anyway)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">03</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">55+ &amp; active adult communities</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The under-considered middle option. A 55+ or active adult community is not assisted living. It is independent housing in a neighborhood designed for adults over 55, usually with shared amenities (clubhouse, pool, fitness center) and age-restricted residency. The good ones produce something most parents do not have at 65: instant community, social structure, built-in activity. The mediocre ones are isolating cul-de-sacs of identical houses where everyone watches television. The difference between the two is enormous and almost completely invisible until you have lived in one for six months. The middle option works for more parents than choose it, mostly because they did not seriously consider it.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> 55+ Communities: The Honest Pros and Cons</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> How to Evaluate a 55+ Community (Without Falling for the Sales Center)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> HOA Fees, Restrictions, and the Hidden Costs of Active Adult Living</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Best 55+ Communities by Region (Updated Annually)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">04</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">CCRC (continuing care)</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">A continuing care retirement community sells you a single solution: independent living now, assisted living when you need it, skilled nursing when you need that. You pay a large entry fee — typically $300,000 to $1 million, sometimes refundable to your estate — plus a monthly fee of $3,000 to $7,000 for the rest of your life. It is expensive. It is also, for the right person, the most rational answer available, because it eliminates the panicked move at 82 from a position of weakness. The decision is made once, in your late 60s or early 70s, while you are still in charge of your own choices. The CCRC industry has predatory operators alongside excellent ones. The financial structures are complex. The wrong contract type can lose you half a million dollars. This sub-pillar is the part of the site where we tell you which contract types to insist on and which to walk away from.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The CCRC Decision: Type A, B, C, and D Contracts Explained</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> CCRC Entry Fees: Refundable, Declining, Non-Refundable — What to Actually Sign</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Evaluating a CCRC's Financial Stability (Before You Hand Them $500K)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The CCRC Wait List: Why You Apply Five Years Before You Plan to Move</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Life Plan Communities: The New Branding, The Same Decision</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">05</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Geographic relocation</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The seven states with no state income tax (Florida, Texas, Tennessee, Nevada, Wyoming, South Dakota, Washington) collectively absorb a disproportionate share of retiree relocations, and not by accident. State tax structure, property tax, sales tax, and estate tax variance can swing your effective retirement income by $5,000 to $25,000 per year. Stack 25 years of that math and the relocation question becomes the largest financial lever in the entire Living pillar. But tax is not the only variable. Proximity to adult children, climate, healthcare access, social network, and the cost of starting over also matter. The decision is harder than the personal finance bloggers make it sound. The default of "stay where you raised the kids" is also a decision — usually the most expensive one available.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Geography of Retirement: The 25-Year Math Most People Don't Run</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> No State Income Tax States: The Real Cost-of-Living Picture</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Moving Near Your Adult Children: How Close Is Too Close?</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Snowbird Strategy: Tax Residency, Two Homes, Real Rules</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Climate, Healthcare, and the Quiet Determinants of Late-Life Geography</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">06</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">International retirement</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Portugal, Costa Rica, Mexico, Panama, Thailand, Spain, and Ecuador all run formal retirement visa programs designed to attract American and Canadian retirees. The math, for a meaningful subset of parents, works: a $4,000-per-month US retirement income produces an upper-middle-class lifestyle in Lisbon or Cuenca that would not even be middle-class in San Francisco. The catch is real: distance from grandchildren, Medicare coverage gaps abroad, language barriers, the political risk of foreign residency, and the one-way nature of the decision. Most parents who consider international retirement do not do it. Some should. The honest analysis is rare in this category because the entire genre is dominated by sponsored content from countries selling residency.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Retiring Abroad: The Honest Math (Not the Sponsored Article)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Top Six Retirement Visa Countries Compared (2026 Update)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Medicare and Healthcare When You Live Abroad</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Reverse Move: When International Retirees Come Back (And Why)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMITMENTS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="commitments">
      <p class="commitments__eyebrow">Our living-content rules</p>
      <h2 class="commitments__title">What we promise on every living page.</h2>
      <div class="commitments__grid">
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">No real-estate-industry sponsorship</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">We do not take sponsorship from CCRCs, 55+ community developers, real estate agencies, senior-living chains, or relocation services. When we name a property, a community, or a chain, it is editorial judgment. When we link to a service, the affiliate relationship is disclosed at the top of the article, not buried at the bottom. The senior-housing industry is unusually predatory; the editorial wall has to be unusually high.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Numbers per region</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Cost of living, property tax, state income tax, and healthcare access vary enormously across the US, Canada, and the international retirement destinations. Articles in this pillar report numbers by state, by region, and by city when relevant — not "varies by location." When data changes (tax rates, CCRC pricing, visa rules), we revise the article and timestamp the update.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">The default is also a decision</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Staying in the house you raised the children in is not the absence of a choice. It is a choice with real financial, social, and physical consequences. We treat the stay-in-place decision with the same rigor as the relocation decision. Sometimes staying is the right answer. We will tell you when, and when not.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Reviewer layer (rolling out)</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on living topics will progressively carry a "Reviewed by [Name, Credential]" line as we bring on credentialed reviewers — a Certified Senior Advisor or Aging Life Care Manager for housing transitions, a CPA for tax-residency content, an elder-law attorney for CCRC contract reviews. Until then, articles in this section are bylined by M. Holloway, the founder, or the AfterChildren Editorial Desk.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- AFFILIATES -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="affiliates">
      <p class="affiliates__eyebrow">Affiliate disclosure</p>
      <h2 class="affiliates__title">What we link to, and what we earn.</h2>
      <p class="affiliates__intro">When we recommend a service, we link to it. When the link earns us a commission, we disclose it. Senior housing and relocation services have a long history of bad actors, including referral networks that get paid more by predatory operators than by ethical ones. We will only link to services that pass an independent quality bar, regardless of commission rate.</p>
      <p class="affiliates__intro affiliates__intro--secondary">As this pillar develops, the partner list below will become live affiliate links. Until then, the list documents the categories under evaluation. Each gets a published review before any link goes live.</p>
      <div class="affiliates__list">
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Senior housing comparison</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Tools to compare 55+ communities, assisted living, and CCRCs by region and price. Under evaluation: A Place for Mom (with caveats about its referral economics), Caring.com, SeniorAdvisor, regional non-profit databases.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Home modification services</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Certified Aging-in-Place Specialists (CAPS) for accessibility renovations, grab bars, walk-in showers, ramps, stairlifts. Under evaluation: National Association of Home Builders CAPS directory (free), Lifeway Mobility, Acorn Stairlifts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Senior move managers</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Professionals who handle downsizing logistics — sorting, donating, estate sales, packing, unpacking, settling into the new place. Under evaluation: National Association of Senior &amp; Specialty Move Managers (NASMM) directory (free).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Geographic relocation tools</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Cost-of-living calculators, state tax comparison, climate data, healthcare quality rankings. Under evaluation: Bankrate's retirement city comparison, AreaVibes, SmartAsset relocation calculator.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">International retirement resources</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Visa application services, expat tax planning, international health insurance. Under evaluation: International Living (with strong caveats — they sell residency packages, treat coverage skeptically), Cigna Global, GeoBlue.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Estate sales &amp; downsizing</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Estate sale companies, online consignment platforms, donation logistics for the household contents that will not move with you. Under evaluation: Everything But The House (EBTH), Maxsold, MaxSold, local estate sale directories.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA: ASK A QUESTION -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="ask">
      <h2 class="ask__title">A living question we should answer?</h2>
      <p class="ask__lede">If a Living topic is on your mind and not on the list above, send it. We read everything. We do not respond individually, but the most-asked questions become next month's articles.</p>
      <p class="ask__contact">Write to <a href="mailto:editor@afterchildren.com">editor@afterchildren.com</a> with subject line "Living: [topic]".</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Newsletter />
</Base>

<style>
